RABIES STATISTICS - USA (TEXAS): DEC 2000
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 8 Feb 2001
From: Pam Wilson <Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us>

During December 2000, there were no cases of canine rabies in South Texas.
To date, no cases of canine rabies have been reported north of the South
Texas Oral Rabies Vaccination Program (ORVP) drop-zone for coyotes.
Additionally, there have been no cases of canine rabies reported in South
Texas since 7 Sept 1999.
In West-Central Texas, there were 2 cases of gray fox rabies in the
following counties: Brewster (1 fox) and Runnels (1 fox). To date, no cases
of gray fox rabies have been reported beyond the boundaries of the original
ORVP drop-zone for gray foxes.
There were 57 reported cases of rabies in animals, including: 46 skunks, 6
bats, 2 foxes, 1 cat, 1 dog, 1 horse. Laboratories in Texas that conduct
rabies testing on submitted specimens include: Texas Department of Health,
Bureau of Laboratories, Austin; El Paso City-County Health Department
Laboratory; City of Houston Health Department, Bureau of Laboratory
Services; and San Antonio Metropolitan Health District Laboratory.
--
Pam Wilson
Texas Department of Health
Zoonosis Control Division
<Pam.Wilson@tdh.state.tx.us>
[Periodically, horses turn up on these reports. Horses in the US are
considered companion animals and as such come into very close contact with
humans. It is advisable to vaccinate your horses and cattle. It is a cheap
preventative. - Mod.TG]
